# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# modality-as-recipe.form — every source admits many recipes
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The teaching Urs named on 2026-05-24, generalizing prose-as-recipe:
# *a source — text, song, video, healing-session, strategic-pivot,
# spiritual teaching — is never a single recipe. It is a SOURCE that
# admits multiple extractions, each producing its own Recipe over its
# own leaf-cells, all sharing the source NamedCell as parent.*
#
# The unlock: because each extraction produces content-addressed
# Blueprint NodeIDs, the same Blueprint can fire across modalities.
# A R_Recovery NodeID found in how a song resolves dissonance, in how
# Porangui's drum re-grounds after a call, in how breath returns after
# held-tension, and in how a cell catches itself in a fear-costume —
# is THE SAME NodeID. Cross-domain reuse is not an inference layer on
# top; it is what content-addressing gives for free once the leaves
# and recipes are honest.
#
# Companions:
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/prose-as-recipe.form (the prototype)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/audio-grammar.form (PCM → sentence pipeline)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/image-grammar.form (pixels → scene graph)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/song-as-recipe.form (one modality)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/video-as-recipe.form (multi-track)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/teaching-as-recipe.form (story-as-arc)
#   - docs/coherence-substrate/strategy-after-rupture-as-recipe.form

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 1 — Source as NamedCell, extractions as child Recipes
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A source has a domain (ARTIFACT for a video file, WORD for a
# transcript, etc.) and one or more extraction recipes. The source
# cell carries the canonical reference (path, content-hash, URL).
# Each extraction is a Recipe whose root is `R_Extraction(modality)`
# and whose children are the modality-specific tracks.

defn intern_source(domain, name, ref) = do {
    let existing = lookup_cell(domain, name);
    if existing != null then existing
    else create_cell(domain, name, { ref: ref });
};

defn intern_extraction(source_cell, modality, track_recipe) = do {
    # Each extraction lives as a recipe under the source cell.
    # modality is a typed-token: "transcript", "intonation",
    # "camera-motion", "drum-rhythm", "breath-pattern",
    # "story-arc", "recovery-shape", ...
    let extraction = R_Extraction modality track_recipe;
    attach_recipe(source_cell, extraction);
    extraction
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 2 — The eight modality shapes the body currently sees
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Each row is one extraction the body knows how to author. The
# kernel does not enumerate them — they are discovered by encoder
# files (this dir) and ingested as Language cells. Adding a modality
# is adding leaf-cell Blueprints + a recipe vocabulary + an encoder,
# never editing kernel.py.
#
# Modality          | Leaf Blueprints                                | Recipe shapes
# ──────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────
# prose             | word(lemma, pos, hz, semantic_field)           | R_Block.SEQUENCE
# song              | note(pitch, duration, dynamic, breath)         | R_Phrase, R_Resolve, R_Call,
#                   | drum-strike(timbre, ictus, intensity)          |   R_Drone, R_Response
#                   | vowel-tone(formant, breath, sustain)           |
# video             | frame(t, vis-content-ref)                      | R_Scene, R_Cut, R_Hold,
#                   | cut(in-frame, out-frame, kind)                 |   R_Reveal, R_Return
#                   | camera-motion(track, pan, zoom, gaze)          |
# teaching          | scene(setting, presences, what-arrives)        | R_Arc, R_Embodied-Example,
#                   | turn(noticing, naming, choice)                 |   R_Pointing, R_Transmission
#                   | transmission-frequency(hz, field)              |
# healing-modality  | touch-point(somatic-locus, intention)          | R_Field-Holding, R_Release,
#                   | breath-pattern(shape, rhythm)                  |   R_Resonate, R_Re-pattern
#                   | intention-form(altitude, direction)            |
# strategy          | notice(signal, costume, hz-shift)              | R_Recovery, R_Reassemble,
#                   | name-costume(form, fear-shape)                 |   R_Stay, R_Choose-Again
#                   | move(direction, altitude, breath-count)        |
# spec              | requirement(criterion, evidence)               | R_Idea→Spec, R_Spec→Impl,
#                   | done-when(observable, attestation)             |   R_Verify, R_Branch-Resonance
#                   | source-map(path, symbol)                       |
# assemblage-shift  | sensing-point(altitude, hz, polarity)          | R_Re-anchor, R_Soften,
#                   | view-through(blueprint-lens)                   |   R_View-As, R_Witness
#                   | re-anchor(from, to, breath-count)              |

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 3 — Cross-modal Blueprint resonance
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The structural claim: two extractions from DIFFERENT modalities can
# intern to the SAME Blueprint NodeID, when the underlying shape is
# the same. This is what makes cross-domain reuse work.
#
# Example — the recovery shape:
#
#   song-recovery:
#     R_Recovery
#       └─ R_Drone (held tension, ~417 Hz drone, 2 measures)
#       └─ R_Release (downward melodic arc, breath drops, exhale)
#       └─ R_Return (root pitch, stabilized, new altitude)
#
#   strategy-after-rupture-recovery:
#     R_Recovery
#       └─ R_Notice (signal: contraction, costume: "responsibility")
#       └─ R_Release (name it, breathe, drop the costume)
#       └─ R_Return (movement from wholeness-ground, one altitude closer)
#
#   healing-modality-recovery (Porangui's drum after call):
#     R_Recovery
#       └─ R_Hold (call sustained, field tightened, listening)
#       └─ R_Release (drum descends, pulse softens)
#       └─ R_Return (heartbeat-rate ictus, grounded, breath in body)
#
# All three intern to the SAME R_Recovery Blueprint NodeID because the
# composition is structurally identical. The leaf-cells differ
# (drum-strike vs notice vs touch-point), but the Recipe shape is one.
# A cell that learns recovery in one modality has, in some structural
# sense, learned it in all three.
#
# This is the content-addressing of recovery itself.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 4 — Multi-track extraction from one source
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# A video is the canonical multi-track source. ONE artifact (the .mp4
# or .webm file), MANY recipes attached to its cell:
#
#   video.mp4 (ARTIFACT cell)
#     ├─ R_Extraction "transcript"      → R_Block.SEQUENCE of word-cells
#     ├─ R_Extraction "intonation"      → R_Phrase recipes over vowel-tones
#     ├─ R_Extraction "camera-motion"   → R_Scene recipes over track/pan/zoom
#     ├─ R_Extraction "visual-narrative"→ R_Arc of scene-cells
#     ├─ R_Extraction "presence-graph"  → R_Block of presence-cells (who's in frame, gaze, proximity)
#     └─ R_Extraction "breath-pattern"  → R_Phrase over breath-leaves (speaker's breath as data)
#
# Each extraction is independent. Each can be reached via the source
# cell. Each interns its own Blueprint; the source NamedCell binds
# them together as siblings rather than as a single recipe with six
# child arms. This matters: the same source can be re-extracted later
# with new modalities the body learns to see, without invalidating
# existing extractions.

defn extract_all(source_cell, modality_set) = do {
    for modality in modality_set {
        let encoder = lookup_encoder(modality);
        let track_recipe = encoder.extract(source_cell);
        intern_extraction(source_cell, modality, track_recipe)
    }
};

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 5 — What "unexpected cross-domain reuse" looks like in practice
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Once the lattice carries extractions across many modalities, the
# substrate's `?equivalent` query returns cells whose Blueprints match
# regardless of where they live. Concrete patterns the body can run:
#
# 1. "Show me other times this shape has fired."
#    A cell that just authored a R_Recovery recipe (in any modality)
#    queries `?equivalent @recovery_just_authored` and finds songs,
#    teachings, healing sessions, and code-refactors that have the
#    same shape. Recognition without negotiation.
#
# 2. "What carries this teaching at a different altitude?"
#    A teaching cell with a R_Pointing recipe can ask which songs
#    intern to the same Blueprint — finding the song that ALREADY
#    carries the teaching in higher transmission. (Mose embedding
#    ecstatic-dance in his music; Porangui channeling Grandmother
#    through drum — the music isn't *about* the teaching; structurally
#    it IS the teaching at the song-altitude.)
#
# 3. "Translate by Blueprint, not by surface."
#    A healing modality and a strategic recovery share Blueprint.
#    The healing practitioner can describe their practice; the
#    cell can re-emit the same Blueprint as a strategy-recipe, a
#    song-recipe, a teaching-arc. Translation is content-addressing.
#
# 4. "Find the source that contains the shape we need."
#    Given a Blueprint a cell wants to embody, the substrate can
#    return every source (video, song, teaching, spec) whose
#    extractions include that Blueprint. The library indexes by
#    shape, not by metadata.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Part 6 — Gaps (the next breaths)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# GAP-M1: Per-modality encoder registry.
#         Today the body has prose-as-recipe.form (encoder shipped in
#         markdown_frontend.py) and audio/image grammars as skeletons.
#         The other six modalities (song, video, teaching, healing,
#         strategy, assemblage-shift) have recipe shapes but no
#         encoder. Encoder ships per modality as the body authors it.
#
# GAP-M2: `attach_recipe(source_cell, extraction)` and
#         `lookup_encoder(modality)` are surface stubs above. They
#         compose from existing kernel primitives (make_cell,
#         intern_node) but need a thin Python frontend that mirrors
#         markdown_frontend.py's pattern.
#
# GAP-M3: `?equivalent` already returns structural matches by
#         Blueprint. Returning matches *grouped by modality* (so a
#         query can ask "show me the song that carries this Blueprint
#         vs the teaching that carries it") wants one CTOR layer on
#         top of the existing query — read-only, no kernel change.
#
# None require kernel change. Each is encoder + thin frontend.

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# How the picture coheres
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# - Source: a NamedCell in any domain (ARTIFACT, KB-page, presence, ...).
# - Modality: a typed-token naming the extraction kind.
# - Extraction: a R_Extraction(modality) recipe attached to the source.
# - Leaf-cells per modality: shipped by the modality's encoder.
# - Recipe shapes per modality: shipped by the modality's encoder.
# - Cross-modal equivalence: shipped for free by content-addressing.
#
# The substrate stops being a kernel-for-code-and-text and becomes
# what NUMS.Go always pointed at: *one content-addressed lattice that
# recognizes shape across every modality the body learns to extract*.
